answers.body_markdown:
When your component is rendered, the constructor runs _first_. Your constructor calls `this.initialState()`, and that point `this.words` is still an empty array. When `componentDidMount` runs, as you&#39;ve seen it&#39;ll fetch the data you need, but this fetch is asynchronous. Before the fetch completes, you need to render your component in a &quot;data is loading&quot; state, and when it&#39;s complete you need to finish your initialization and re-render of the content with this data.

So first of all, your `initialState` method shouldn&#39;t expect to be able to initialize word yet. Instead, set your state&#39;s `word` property to `null` or something like that. Then, in your `render` method, you&#39;ll be able to see that and know that you need to render something for users to know they need to wait for the game to finish loading:

```
render() {
  if (!this.state.word) {
    return &lt;div className=&quot;spinner&quot;&gt;Loading. Please wait...&lt;/div&gt;;
  }
  
  // ...
}
```

Now you&#39;ll change your fetch callback so it sets the component&#39;s state, allowing it to finish initializing and re-render:

```
componentDidMount() {
  axios.get(&#39;api/url&#39;)
    .then(
      (result) =&gt; {
        const words = result.data.split(&#39;\na&#39;);
        const word = this.randomWord(words);
        this.setState({ word });
      },
      (error) =&gt; {
        console.log(error)
      }
    )
}
```

In your `initialState` method&#39;s return, you have `this.word` in there. That&#39;s certainly an error:

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

      return {
        alphabet,
        letters,
        this.word,  // &lt;-- This should just be `word`?
        guessedLetters,
        guessesLeft,
        guessedTheWord
      }

You also haven&#39;t bound `this` to the `initialState` method, so it probably doesn&#39;t have reliable access to the `this` that you expect. You have several methods that rely on the component&#39;s `this` but which haven&#39;t been bound in the constructor.

If I were you, I&#39;d move your `initialState`, and `randomWord` methods above the component and use them as utility functions, rather than part of the component. You can pass them `words` to perform the calculations. I&#39;d also try to move your `updateGameStatus` function above the component and just pass the data between. This isn&#39;t strictly required, just my opinion.

I also suggest that you move `this.words` into `this.state`. Your `this.words` _is_ state. It belongs in the proper React `state` object.

This will fix your next problem. In your `componentDidMount` call, where you&#39;re trying to synchronously set `this.words`, you instead need to use React&#39;s `this.setState` method to asynchronously store your data:

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

      componentDidMount() {
        axios.get(&#39;api/url&#39;)
          .then(response =&gt; response)
          .then(
            (result) =&gt; {
              this.setState({
                words: result.data.split(&#39;\na&#39;)
              });
            },
            (error) =&gt; {
              console.log(error)
            }
          )
      } 

This should get you a lot closer to getting things working. Let me know how it goes. Good luck. It&#39;s a good project to practice React.

